"Greater Bay Area in the Eyes of Artists," an exhibition celebrating the 25th anniversary of Hong Kong's return to the motherland, opened at the National Museum of China in Beijing on Friday. A total of 116 pieces of artworks by artists from the Chinese mainland, Hong Kong and Macao are on display. The exhibition will last until July 2. Then, it will be exhibited on tour in Hong Kong, Macao, and Shenzhen. The works include the achievements of the Communist Party of China over the past century and record the innovative practices depicted in the Greater Bay Area of Guangdong, Hong Kong and Macao. Among the exhibits, artist Han Mei's "A Taste of Hong Kong," depicting 30 tempting authentic snacks, has attracted many visitors. The sculpture "Home" created by Hong Kong sculptor Chu Tat-Shing also appears to be unique.